# Project Routing

## Routing Table

| What it is | Where it lives |
|---|---|
| Canonical API client pattern (read, don't import) | projects/_reference/clients/ |
| Canonical data schema (read, don't import) | projects/_reference/schemas/ |
| A self-contained project | projects/<project-name>/ |
| Project credential template | projects/<project-name>/.env.example |
| Project config loader | projects/<project-name>/config.py |
| Project's copy of a client | projects/<project-name>/clients/ |
| Project's copy of a schema | projects/<project-name>/schemas/ |

## Critical Rules

**Projects are standalone bubbles.**
Every project owns its own config, schemas, clients, and credentials.
Nothing imports from _reference/ — it copies from it.

```
# WRONG
from _reference.clients.jira import JiraClient

# RIGHT
# cp _reference/clients/jira.py my-project/clients/jira.py
# project owns its copy
```

**Credentials are isolated per project.**
- Root `.env` = master credential store (never committed, never used by code directly)
- Project `.env` = project's own copy of the credentials it needs (never committed)
- Project `.env.example` = committed template showing what keys are needed (no real values)

**Starting a new project:**
1. mkdir projects/new-project-name/
2. Copy relevant files from _reference/ into it
3. Create .env.example listing only the credentials this project needs
4. Build in isolation — no shared dependencies

**Containerization readiness:**
Because every project is already self-contained, containerizing means adding a
Dockerfile — no untangling of dependencies required.
